Basic Pandas¶

In a sense, pandas is built "on top" of NumPy. For example, NumPy universal functions will generally work on pandas objects as well. We therefore import both to begin with.

On a rather fundamental level, the DataFrame class is designed to manage indexed and labeled data.

Changing numbers format in Pandas Dataframe¶

The following example already shows some major features of the DataFrame class when it comes to storing data:

  • data: data itself can be provided in different shapes and types
  • labels: data is organized in columns which can have custom names
  • index: there is an index that can take on different formats
In [20]:
df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(2, 2))
df
Out[20]:
0 1
0 0.498840 -0.994254
1 2.355705 -1.518300
In [21]:
df[1] = df[1].map('${:,.2f}'.format)
df[1]
Out[21]:
0    $-0.99
1    $-1.52
Name: 1, dtype: object
In [22]:
df[0] = pd.Series(["{0:.2f}%".format(val * 100) for val in df[0]], 
                  index = df.index)
df[0]
Out[22]:
0     49.88%
1    235.57%
Name: 0, dtype: object

Indexing options:¶

ParameterFormat
obj[val] Select single column or sequence of columns
obj.ix[val] Select single row or subset of rows
obj.ix[:,val] Select single column or subset of columns
obj.ix[val1,val2] Select both rows and columns
icol,irow Select single column or row, as a Series by integer location
get_value, set_value Select single value by row and column label

Date Ranges using Pandas¶

Out[3]:
DatetimeIndex(['2017-01-31', '2017-02-28', '2017-03-31', '2017-04-30',
               '2017-05-31', '2017-06-30', '2017-07-31', '2017-08-31',
               '2017-09-30'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='M')

Date_range function:¶

ParameterFormatDescription
start string/datetime left bound for generating dates
end string/datetime right bound for generating dates
periods integer/None number of periods(if start or end are None)
freq string/Dateoffset frequency string , 5D for five days
tz string/None time zone name for localized index
normalize bool, default None normalize start and end to midnight
name string, default None name of resulting index

Frequency parameter values:¶

AliasDescription
B Business day frequency
C Custom business day frequency
D Calendar day frequency
W Weekly frequency
M Month end frequency
BM Business month end frequency
MS Month start frequency
BMS Business month start frequency
Q Quarter end frequency
BQ Business quarter end frequency
QS Quarter start frequency
BQS Business Quarter start frequency
A Year end frequency
BA Business year end frequency
AS Year start frequency
BAS Business year start frequency
H Hourly frequency
M Minutely frequency
S Secondly frequency
L Miliseconds frequency
U Microseconds frequency

Important link to learn Merge, join, Concatenate¶

1. Merge: Similar to SQL join operation, using relational data
2. concat: glues or stacks together objects along the axis
3. combine_first: enables splicing together overlapping data to fill 
   in missing values in one object with values from another
ArgumentDescription
left Dataframe to be merged on the left side
right Dataframe to be merged on the right side
how one of 'inner' or 'outer', 'left', 'right', 'inner' by default
on Column name for the merge, Must be found on both Dataframe objects.
left_on Columns on the left Dataframe to use as join keys
right_on Columns on the right Dataframe to use as join keys
sort sort merged data by lexicographically by join keys, true by default
suffixes Tupple of string values to append to column names in case of overlap; defaults('_x','_y')

Merge, Join, and Concatenate

How to apply a formula to every row of a dataframe¶

In [3]:
def f(row):
    if row['Period'] == 'monthly' and row['Category'] == 'HRCost' and row['Label'] != 'Emirati':
        val = row['Values'] * (1 + parameter.ix['Visa_Cost'][0] + parameter.ix['Health_Care'][0]\
                                    * (1 + parameter.ix['Buffer'][0])) * parameter.ix['Month'][0]
    
    elif row['Period'] == 'monthly' and row['Category'] == 'HRCost' and row['Label'] == 'Emirati':
        val = row['Values'] * (1 + parameter.ix['Health_Care'][0]\
                                    * (1 + parameter.ix['Buffer'][0])) * parameter.ix['Month'][0]
    
    elif row['Period'] == 'monthly' and row['Category'] == 'FixedCost':
        val = row['Values'] * (1 + parameter.ix['Buffer_Exp'][0]) * parameter.ix['Month'][0]
    
    else:
        val = 0
    
    return val
